{"title_page": "Kota State", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \n|conventional_long_name =Kota State<br>Kotah State\n|common_name = Kotah \n|nation      = [[British India]]\n|subdivision = [[Princely State]]\n|era         = \n|year_start  = 1631\n|date_start  = \n|event_start = \n|year_end    = 1949\n|date_end    = \n|event_end   = [[Independence of India]]\n|event1      = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1          =\n|s1          = India\n|flag_p1     = \n|flag_s1     = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag  = Kota Garuda Flag.jpg\n|image_coat  = Kota State CoA.png\n|image_map    = Jhalawar-Tonk map.jpg\n|image_map_caption =Kota State in the [[Imperial Gazetteer of India]]\n|stat_area1   = 14828\n|stat_year1  = 1931\n|stat_pop1   = 685,804\n|today       = [[Rajasthan]], [[India]] \n|footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Kota State''', also known as '''Kotah State''',<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Kotah |volume=15 |page=919}}</ref> was a state in India, centered on the city of [[Kota, Rajasthan|Kota]], now located in [[Rajasthan State]] of the [[India]].\n\nThe town of Kota was once the part of the erstwhile kingdom of [[Bundi State|Bundi]]. It became a separate princely state in the 17th century. The state belonged to the Kotah-Jhalawar Agency which had headquarters at Kota and was a subdivision of the [[Rajputana Agency]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Maharao Ram Singh II of Kota (reigned 1827-1866) Hunting with Maharao Ram Singh of Bundi (reigned 1828-1866) LACMA M.75.19 (2 of 9).jpg|thumb|275px|Maharao Ram Singh II of Kota (reigned 1828\u20131866) Hunting with Maharao Ram Singh of Bundi (reigned 1828\u20131866)]]\n\n[[File:3 Melancholy Courtesan Bundi or Kota 1610 Metmuseum.jpg|thumb|230px|Melancholy [[courtesan]] of Kota or Bundi palace. 1610]]\n\nIn 1631 Kota state seceded from Bundi State. Between 18 June 1707 and 8 September 1713 it was briefly reunited with Bundi again.\nOn 26 December 1817 Kota state became a [[British protectorate]] who were granted a [[Salute state|hereditary salute of 17 guns]] by the British.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nThe average revenue of Kota state in 1901 was Rs.31,00,000. <ref>https://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V15_427.gif</ref>\n\n[[File:Marriage of M.K. Bhim Singh of Kotah.jpg|thumb|270px|Marriage of Maharaja Bhim Singh II of Kotah.]]\n\n==Rulers==\nThe rulers of Kota were from the Hada sept of the Chauhan Rajput clan and bore the title of Maharao.<ref>https://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V15_418.gif</ref><ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_K-W.html Indian Princely States]</ref>\n===Maharaos===\n*Apr 1696 \u2013 18 June 1707: Ram Singh I: (b. 16.. \u2013 d. 1707) \n*18 Jun 1707 \u2013  8 September 1713: interregnum\n* 8 September 1713 \u2013 19 June 1720: Bhim Singh I: (b. 1682 \u2013 d. 1720) \n*19 Jun 1720 \u2013 Oct 1723: Arjun Singh: (d. 1723) \n*Oct 1723 \u2013 1 August 1756: Durjan Sal: (d. 1756) \n*1756 \u2013 Mar 1757: Ajit Singh: (b. bf. 1676 \u2013 d. 1757) \n*Mar 1757 \u2013 17 December 1764: Chhatar Sal Singh I: (b. bf.1718 \u2013 d. 1764) \n*17 Dec 1764 \u2013 17 January 1771: Guman Singh: (b. 1724 \u2013 d. 1771) \n*17 Jan 1771 \u2013 19 November 1819: Umaid Singh I: (b. 1761 \u2013 d. 1819) \n*19 Nov 1819 \u2013 20 July 1828: Kishor Singh II: (b. c. 1781 \u2013 d. 1828) \n*20 Jul 1828 \u2013 27 March 1866: Ram Singh II: (b. 1808 \u2013 d. 1866) \n*27 Mar 1866 \u2013 11 June 1889: Chhatar Sal Singh II: (b. 1837 \u2013 d. 1889) \n*11 Jun 1889 \u2013 27 December 1940: [[Umed Singh II]]: (b. 1873 \u2013 d. 1940) (from 23 May 1900, Sir Umed Singh II)\n*11 Jun 1889 \u2013  5 December 1896: .... \u2013 Regent\n*27 Dec 1940 \u2013 18 April 1948: [[Bhim Singh II]]: (b. 1909 \u2013 d. 1991)\n\n===Titular Maharaos===\nOn 18 April 1948, the Maharao merged his state with the [[Dominion of India|union of India]] and the state thus ceased to have independent existence. The Maharao lost his ruling powers but continued to hold certain titles and privileges until 1971, when everything was withdrawn. Nevertheless, the Maharao remains the head of the erstwhile royal family and an important cultural figure in Kota. The non-ruling Maharaos are listed below:\n*27 Dec 1940 \u2013 18 April 1948 \u2013 21 June 1991: [[Bhim Singh II]]: (b. 1909 \u2013 d. 1991); last ruling Maharao. \n*21 June 1991 \u2013 present: [[Brijraj Singh]]\n*The heir apparent is [[Ijyaraj Singh]], only son of Maharao Brijraj Singh\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Hadoti]]\n*[[Political integration of India]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat inline}}\n{{Princely states of India}}\n\n{{coord|25.18|N|75.83|E|region:IN_type:landmark_source:kolossus-svwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Princely states of India]]\n[[Category:Kota district]]\n[[Category:History of Kota, Rajasthan]]\n\n\n{{Rajasthan-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \n|conventional_long_name =Kota State<br>Kotah State\n|common_name = Kotah \n|nation      = [[British India]]\n|subdivision = [[Princely State]]\n|era         = \n|year_start  = 1631\n|date_start  = \n|event_start = \n|year_end    = 1949\n|date_end    = \n|event_end   = [[Independence of India]]\n|event1      = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1          =\n|s1          = India\n|flag_p1     = \n|flag_s1     = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag  = Kota Garuda Flag.jpg\n|image_coat  = Kota State CoA.png\n|image_map    = Jhalawar-Tonk map.jpg\n|image_map_caption =Kota State in the [[Imperial Gazetteer of India]]\n|stat_area1   = 14828\n|stat_year1  = 1931\n|stat_pop1   = 685,804\n|today       = [[Rajasthan]], [[India]] \n|footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Kota State''', also known as '''Kotah State''',<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Kotah |volume=15 |page=919}}</ref> was a state in India, centered on the city of [[Kota, Rajasthan|Kota]], now located in [[Rajasthan State]] of the [[India]].\n\nThe town of Kota was once the part of the erstwhile kingdom of [[Bundi State|Bundi]]. It became a separate princely state in the 17th century. The state belonged to the Kotah-Jhalawar Agency which had headquarters at Kota and was a subdivision of the [[Rajputana Agency]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Maharao Ram Singh II of Kota (reigned 1827-1866) Hunting with Maharao Ram Singh of Bundi (reigned 1828-1866) LACMA M.75.19 (2 of 9).jpg|thumb|275px|Maharao Ram Singh II of Kota (reigned 1828-1866) Hunting with Maharao Ram Singh of Bundi (reigned 1828-1866)]]\n\n[[File:3 Melancholy Courtesan Bundi or Kota 1610 Metmuseum.jpg|thumb|230px|Melancholy [[courtesan]] of Kota or Bundi palace. 1610]]\n\nIn 1631 Kota state seceded from Bundi State. Between 18 Jun 1707 and 8 Sep 1713 it was briefly reunited with Bundi again.\nOn 26 Dec 1817 Kota state became a [[British protectorate]] who were granted a [[Salute state|hereditary salute of 17 guns]] by the British.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nThe average revenue of Kota state in 1901 was Rs.31,00,000. <ref>https://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V15_427.gif</ref>\n\n[[File:Marriage of M.K. Bhim Singh of Kotah.jpg|thumb|270px|Marriage of Maharaja Bhim Singh II of Kotah.]]\n\n==Rulers==\nThe rulers of Kota were from the Hada sept of the Chauhan Rajput clan and bore the title of Maharao.<ref>https://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V15_418.gif</ref><ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_K-W.html Indian Princely States]</ref>\n===Maharaos===\n*Apr 1696 \u2013 18 Jun 1707: Ram Singh I: (b. 16.. \u2013 d. 1707) \n*18 Jun 1707 \u2013  8 Sep 1713: interregnum\n* 8 Sep 1713 \u2013 19 Jun 1720: Bhim Singh I: (b. 1682 \u2013 d. 1720) \n*19 Jun 1720 \u2013 Oct 1723: Arjun Singh: (d. 1723) \n*Oct 1723 \u2013 1 Aug 1756: Durjan Sal: (d. 1756) \n*1756 \u2013 Mar 1757: Ajit Singh: (b. bf. 1676 \u2013 d. 1757) \n*Mar 1757 \u2013 17 Dec 1764: Chhatar Sal Singh I: (b. bf.1718 \u2013 d. 1764) \n*17 Dec 1764 \u2013 17 Jan 1771: Guman Singh: (b. 1724 \u2013 d. 1771) \n*17 Jan 1771 \u2013 19 Nov 1819: Umaid Singh I: (b. 1761 \u2013 d. 1819) \n*19 Nov 1819 \u2013 20 Jul 1828: Kishor Singh II: (b. c. 1781 \u2013 d. 1828) \n*20 Jul 1828 \u2013 27 Mar 1866: Ram Singh II: (b. 1808 \u2013 d. 1866) \n*27 Mar 1866 \u2013 11 Jun 1889: Chhatar Sal Singh II: (b. 1837 \u2013 d. 1889) \n*11 Jun 1889 \u2013 27 Dec 1940: [[Umed Singh II]]: (b. 1873 \u2013 d. 1940) (from 23 May 1900, Sir Umed Singh II)\n*11 Jun 1889 \u2013  5 Dec 1896: .... \u2013 Regent\n*27 Dec 1940 \u2013 18 April 1948: [[Bhim Singh II]]: (b. 1909 \u2013 d. 1991)\n\n===Titular Maharaos===\nOn 18 April 1948, the Maharao merged his state with the [[union of India]] and the state thus ceased to have independent existence. The Maharao lost his ruling powers but continued to hold certain titles and privileges until 1971, when everything was withdrawn. Nevertheless, the Maharao remains the head of the erstwhile royal family and an important cultural figure in Kota. The non-ruling Maharaos are listed below:\n*27 Dec 1940 \u2013 18 April 1948 - 21 June 1991: [[Bhim Singh II]]: (b. 1909 \u2013 d. 1991); last ruling Maharao. \n*21 June 1991 - present: [[Brijraj Singh]]\n*The heir apparent is [[Ijyaraj Singh]], only son of Maharao Brijraj Singh\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Hadoti]]\n*[[Political integration of India]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat inline}}\n{{Princely states of India}}\n\n{{coord|25.18|N|75.83|E|region:IN_type:landmark_source:kolossus-svwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Princely states of India]]\n[[Category:Kota district]]\n[[Category:History of Kota, Rajasthan]]\n\n\n{{Rajasthan-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DrKay", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript, date formats 